ce:section.ce:para:
The selected study site for the river water analysis was the Brahmaputra River. Previous studies have illustrated that the river water contains various ionic species, organic matter and elevated heavy metal concentrations [53–55]. Taking this contaminants into account, the river was chosen and the water samples were compiled for analysis at nearby Public Health Engineering Department (PHED). A comprehensive analysis of the river for multiple parameters available were done including the heavy metal concentrations (
                           Fig. S5
                        ). Among the detected parameters, the concentration of heavy metal Iron was found to be exceeding the permissible limits, thereby rendering it unsuitable for irrigation purposes as well as other activities. To address this issue 1,10-phenanthroline method was used to analyze and quantify the iron content. The results obtained from PHED revealed that Iron content in the river water samples was found to be 4.89 mg/L which is significantly higher than the permissible limit. Such amount of concentrations pose serious threats to public health, indicating that the water is unfit for domestic use without proper treatment.
